<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,2007]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,265,541,567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Remarks</emphasis>
. The generic placement of the new species is uncertain, being close to both 
<taxonomicName authority="Guinot, 1967" authorityName="Guinot" authorityYear="1967" box="[1148,1431,541,567]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1148,1269,541,566]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[1275,1431,541,567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot, 
<number box="[1370,1431,541,567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Guinot, 1967" authorityName="Guinot" authorityYear="1967" box="[202,506,581,607]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[202,339,581,606]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[347,506,581,607]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot, 
<number box="[444,506,581,607]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[520,640,581,606]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[520,640,581,606]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was established for two species formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Dana 1852" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1260,1366,581,606]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeus</emphasis>
Dana 
<number box="[151,214,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1852.0">1852</number>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Haswell, 1882" authorityName="Haswell" authorityYear="1882" box="[225,592,621,647]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosus">
<emphasis box="[225,395,621,646]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. granulosus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Haswell" box="[411,583,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Haswell, W. A. (1882) On some new Australian Brachyura. Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales, 6 (3), 540 - 551." type="journal article" year="1882">
Haswell, 
<number box="[523,583,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1882.0">1882</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[608,660,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
species by designation) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Balss, 1922" authorityName="Balss" authorityYear="1922" box="[999,1313,621,647]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglectus">
<emphasis box="[999,1150,621,646]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. neglectus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Balss" box="[1165,1305,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Balss, H. (1922) Crustacea VII. Decapoda Brachyura (Oxyrhyncha and Brachyrhyncha) und geographischte Ubersicht Crustacea Decapoda. In: W. Michaelsen, Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Meeresfauna Westafrika, 3 (3), 69 - 110." type="journal article" year="1922">
Balss, 
<number box="[1245,1305,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1922.0">1922</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as well as a new species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Guinot, 1967" authorityName="Guinot" authorityYear="1967" box="[333,651,661,687]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">
<emphasis box="[333,481,661,686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. edwardsi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[490,651,661,687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot, 
<number box="[589,651,661,687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. A clear diagnosis of the genus was unfortunately not given. The most important characters she employed in characterizing 
<taxonomicName box="[876,997,701,726]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[876,997,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and separating it from 
<taxonomicName authority="Guinot, 1967" authorityName="Guinot" authorityYear="1967" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[151,312,741,767]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot, 
<number box="[251,312,741,767]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, were the relative lengths of the ambulatory legs and cheliped fingers both being shorter in 
<emphasis box="[151,279,781,806]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName box="[151,276,781,806]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Medaeops</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Other characters stated were the relative prominence of the carapace regions, the degree to which the thoracic sternum was swollen, the arrangements and sizes of the articles of the antennules and antennae, and the form of the G 
<number box="[407,418,861,887]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
, which narrows distally and is quite strongly curved, with sometimes a sub-distal patch of long setae. There have been only two major publications dealing with 
<taxonomicName box="[1003,1123,901,926]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1123,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since 
<number box="[1197,1260,901,927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Serene" box="[1271,1436,901,927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Serene, R. (1984) Crustaces Decapodes Brachyoures de l'Ocean Indien occidental et de la Mer Rouge. Xanthoidea: Xanthidae et Trapeziidae. Addendum Carpiliidae et Menippidae - A. Crosnier. Faune Tropicale, 24, 1 - 400, pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1984">
Serène (
<number box="[1366,1427,901,927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Davie" box="[201,361,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Davie, P. J. F. (1997) Crustacea Decapoda: Deep water Xanthoidea from the South-Western Pacific and Western Indian Ocean. In: A. Crosnier (editor), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, vol. 18. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle (Paris), 176, 337 - 387." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Davie (
<number box="[289,353,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1997.0">1997</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Serene" box="[374,539,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Serene, R. (1984) Crustaces Decapodes Brachyoures de l'Ocean Indien occidental et de la Mer Rouge. Xanthoidea: Xanthidae et Trapeziidae. Addendum Carpiliidae et Menippidae - A. Crosnier. Faune Tropicale, 24, 1 - 400, pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1984">
Serène (
<number box="[470,531,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
did not discuss the genus at any length and his key (
<bibRefCitation author="Serene" box="[1167,1362,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Serene, R. (1984) Crustaces Decapodes Brachyoures de l'Ocean Indien occidental et de la Mer Rouge. Xanthoidea: Xanthidae et Trapeziidae. Addendum Carpiliidae et Menippidae - A. Crosnier. Faune Tropicale, 24, 1 - 400, pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1984">
Serène 
<number box="[1256,1319,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1984.0">1984</number>
: 
<number box="[1332,1362,941,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="91.0">91</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) basically separated 
<taxonomicName box="[333,454,981,1006]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[333,454,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the allied 
<taxonomicName box="[642,803,981,1006]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Paramedaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[642,803,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Paramedaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[861,998,981,1006]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[861,998,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its members possessing relatively lower carapace regions, proportionately more elongated cheliped fingers, the merus of the fifth ambulatory leg being relatively short (about three times longer than broad), a semicircular telson, and a relatively straighter G 
<number box="[178,189,1101,1127]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Davie" box="[202,357,1101,1127]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Davie, P. J. F. (1997) Crustacea Decapoda: Deep water Xanthoidea from the South-Western Pacific and Western Indian Ocean. In: A. Crosnier (editor), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, vol. 18. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle (Paris), 176, 337 - 387." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Davie (
<number box="[288,349,1101,1127]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1997.0">1997</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described two new species (
<taxonomicName box="[696,872,1101,1126]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merodontos">
<emphasis box="[696,872,1101,1126]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. merodontos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[930,1049,1101,1126]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemini">
<emphasis box="[930,1049,1101,1126]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. gemini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and provided a new key (
<bibRefCitation author="Davie" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Davie, P. J. F. (1997) Crustacea Decapoda: Deep water Xanthoidea from the South-Western Pacific and Western Indian Ocean. In: A. Crosnier (editor), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, vol. 18. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle (Paris), 176, 337 - 387." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Davie 
<number box="[151,214,1141,1167]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1997.0">1997</number>
: 
<number box="[225,273,1141,1167]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="357.0">357</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), but remarked it was difficult to distinguish 
<taxonomicName box="[800,921,1141,1166]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[800,921,1141,1166]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[992,1129,1141,1166]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[992,1129,1141,1166]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because most of the characters used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[329,497,1181,1207]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot (
<number box="[427,488,1181,1207]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
were variable. He noted that the primary reasons why he referred his two new species to 
<taxonomicName box="[282,403,1221,1246]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[282,403,1221,1246]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and not 
<taxonomicName box="[517,654,1221,1246]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[517,654,1221,1246]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were because the meri of their ambulatory legs were relatively shorter and the fingers of the chelipeds are neither long nor incurved. 
<taxonomicName box="[969,1106,1261,1286]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[969,1106,1261,1286]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are known from the western Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[421,757,1301,1327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. &amp; Macpherson, E. (1988). Remarques sur la genre Monodaeus Guinot, 1967, avec la description de deux espces nouvelles (Crustacea: Decapoda: Brachyura). Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 4, 10 (4), 731 - 757." type="journal article" year="1988">
Guinot &amp; Macpherson 
<number box="[694,757,1301,1327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,2007]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
While most of the species now included in 
<taxonomicName box="[723,844,1341,1366]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[723,844,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be related, there is no suite of existing characters that are really shared by all species. The 
<typeStatus box="[753,803,1381,1407]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName box="[909,1078,1381,1406]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosus">
<emphasis box="[909,1078,1381,1406]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. granulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is the most widespread member of the genus and is actually the easiest species to diagnose. It is the only member of the genus with distinctly carinate ambulatory legs, especially along the margins of the meri, and its G 
<number box="[1144,1155,1461,1487]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
is the stoutest, with the proximal two-thirds straight and stout, and the distal third more slender and lined with long setae nearer the tip (
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[159,415,1541,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot 
<number box="[251,314,1541,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
: Fig. 
<number box="[381,415,1541,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="40.0">40</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[686,806,1541,1566]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[686,806,1541,1566]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the meri of their ambulatory legs granulated or serrated, but never carinate. The G 
<number box="[560,571,1581,1607]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
s of 
<taxonomicName box="[621,771,1581,1606]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglectus">
<emphasis box="[621,771,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. neglectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[827,973,1581,1606]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">
<emphasis box="[827,973,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. edwardsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also relatively stout with long setae on the distal-most parts, but they do not have the characteristic form of the G 
<number box="[1054,1065,1621,1647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1104,1273,1621,1646]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosus">
<emphasis box="[1104,1273,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. granulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being gradually tapering throughout their length (
<bibRefCitation author="Serene" box="[599,911,1661,1687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Serene, R. (1984) Crustaces Decapodes Brachyoures de l'Ocean Indien occidental et de la Mer Rouge. Xanthoidea: Xanthidae et Trapeziidae. Addendum Carpiliidae et Menippidae - A. Crosnier. Faune Tropicale, 24, 1 - 400, pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1984">
Serène 
<number box="[689,752,1661,1687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1984.0">1984</number>
: Figs. 52, 53
</bibRefCitation>
). The G 
<number box="[1013,1024,1661,1687]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
s of 
<taxonomicName box="[1077,1255,1661,1686]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merodontos">
<emphasis box="[1077,1255,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. merodontos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1316,1436,1661,1686]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemini">
<emphasis box="[1316,1436,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. gemini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very slender (closely resembling that of the new species described here, 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1163,1701,1726]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serenei">
<emphasis box="[1040,1163,1701,1726]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. serenei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and gently tapering to a sharp tip, with the distal-most parts having scattered short setae at best (
<bibRefCitation author="Davie" box="[1007,1149,1741,1767]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Davie, P. J. F. (1997) Crustacea Decapoda: Deep water Xanthoidea from the South-Western Pacific and Western Indian Ocean. In: A. Crosnier (editor), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, vol. 18. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle (Paris), 176, 337 - 387." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Davie 
<number box="[1086,1149,1741,1767]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[1160,1240,1741,1767]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,255,1623,1647]" captionTargetBox="[157,1417,218,1571]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Medaeops serenei, new species. Holotype male. A, third maxillipeds; B, male abdominal segments 3 – 5, 6 and telson; C, right fourth ambulatory leg; D, left G 1; E, left G 2. Scales A, B = 2.0 mm; C = 5.0 mm; D, E = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/177165/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Figs. 
<quantity box="[1224,1240,1741,1767]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="7.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" unit="g" value="7.0">7</quantity>
</figureCitation>
g, h; 
<quantity box="[1298,1330,1741,1767]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="8.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" unit="g" value="8.0">8g</quantity>
, h). 
<collectingCountry box="[1380,1413,1741,1767]" name="American Samoa" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">As</collectingCountry>
it stands, it would be more parsimonious to restrict 
<taxonomicName box="[740,861,1781,1806]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[740,861,1781,1806]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[900,1070,1781,1806]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosus">
<emphasis box="[900,1070,1781,1806]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. granulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This of course begs the question as to what to do with the remaining 
<taxonomicName box="[625,745,1821,1846]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[625,745,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,541,2007]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,152,578]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="44" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
In general carapace form, the other 
<taxonomicName box="[634,755,1861,1886]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[634,755,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<taxonomicName box="[870,1022,1861,1886]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglectus">
<emphasis box="[870,1022,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. neglectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1041,1189,1861,1886]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">
<emphasis box="[1041,1189,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. edwardsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1207,1386,1861,1886]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merodontos">
<emphasis box="[1207,1386,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. merodontos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. gemini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[292,416,1901,1926]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serenei" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[292,416,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. serenei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[434,578,1901,1927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
) are actually closer to 
<taxonomicName box="[856,993,1901,1926]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[856,993,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. 
<collectingCountry box="[1104,1137,1901,1927]" name="American Samoa" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">As</collectingCountry>
noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[1260,1431,1901,1927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. (1967) Recherches preliminaires sur les groupements naturels chez Crustacs Decapodes Brachyoures. II. Les anciens genres Micropanope Stimpson et Medaeus Dana. Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 2, 39 (2), 345 - 374." type="journal article" year="1967">
Guinot (
<number box="[1359,1422,1901,1927]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1967.0">1967</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Serene" box="[151,321,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Serene, R. (1984) Crustaces Decapodes Brachyoures de l'Ocean Indien occidental et de la Mer Rouge. Xanthoidea: Xanthidae et Trapeziidae. Addendum Carpiliidae et Menippidae - A. Crosnier. Faune Tropicale, 24, 1 - 400, pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1984">
Serène (
<number box="[249,312,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[335,693,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. &amp; Macpherson, E. (1988). Remarques sur la genre Monodaeus Guinot, 1967, avec la description de deux espces nouvelles (Crustacea: Decapoda: Brachyura). Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 4, 10 (4), 731 - 757." type="journal article" year="1988">
Guinot &amp; Macpherson (
<number box="[623,684,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1988.0">1988</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Davie" box="[754,914,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Davie, P. J. F. (1997) Crustacea Decapoda: Deep water Xanthoidea from the South-Western Pacific and Western Indian Ocean. In: A. Crosnier (editor), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, vol. 18. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle (Paris), 176, 337 - 387." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Davie (
<number box="[842,905,1941,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1997.0">1997</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the fingers of the chelipeds of 
<taxonomicName box="[1299,1436,1941,1966]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are generally very long and curved, although this is not always the case, those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Rathbun, 1911" authorityName="Rathbun" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="44" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculidens">
<emphasis box="[1236,1436,1981,2006]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">M. tuberculidens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun" box="[159,335,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" refString="Rathbun, M. J. (1911) No XI. - Marine Brachyura, In: The Percy Sladen Trust Expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905 under the leadership of Mr. J. Stanley Gardiner, Volume III,. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, (2) 14 (2), 191 - 261, pls 15 - 20." type="journal article" year="1911">
Rathbun, 
<number box="[276,335,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1911.0">1911</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
are relatively short as well (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[730,1068,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. &amp; Macpherson, E. (1988). Remarques sur la genre Monodaeus Guinot, 1967, avec la description de deux espces nouvelles (Crustacea: Decapoda: Brachyura). Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 4, 10 (4), 731 - 757." type="journal article" year="1988">
Guinot &amp; Macpherson 
<number box="[1005,1068,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: Pl. 
<number box="[1121,1137,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="2.0">2</number>
C). Similarly, the proportions of the legs are also not a reliable generic character as it does vary (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Guinot" box="[1081,1423,192,218]" pageId="7" pageNumber="50" refString="Guinot, D. &amp; Macpherson, E. (1988). Remarques sur la genre Monodaeus Guinot, 1967, avec la description de deux espces nouvelles (Crustacea: Decapoda: Brachyura). Bulletin du Musum national d'Histoire naturelle (Paris), ser. 4, 10 (4), 731 - 757." type="journal article" year="1988">
Guinot &amp; Macpherson 
<number box="[1360,1423,192,218]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). While 
<taxonomicName box="[231,383,232,257]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neglectus">
<emphasis box="[231,383,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">M. neglectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[443,590,232,257]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">
<emphasis box="[443,590,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">M. edwardsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be included in 
<taxonomicName box="[837,974,232,257]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[837,974,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this is not the case for the other three species. 
<taxonomicName box="[252,518,272,297]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merodontos">
<emphasis box="[252,518,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Medaeops merodontos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[534,655,272,297]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemini">
<emphasis box="[534,655,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">M. gemini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[715,838,272,297]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serenei">
<emphasis box="[715,838,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">M. serenei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can easily be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[1242,1379,272,297]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1242,1379,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in the form of the G 
<number box="[450,462,312,338]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" value="1.0">1</number>
: long and slender, with the distal-most margins possessing short setae versus relatively stouter with a stocky basal part and numerous long setae on the distal-most margins in 
<taxonomicName box="[1242,1379,352,377]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1242,1379,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,152,578]" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">
Even though the present new species significantly broadens the generic boundaries of 
<taxonomicName box="[1203,1324,392,417]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Medaeops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1324,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Medaeops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
even further, especially with regards to its relatively long ambulatory legs, we choose to include the new species in this genus rather than in 
<taxonomicName box="[445,582,472,497]" class="Malacostraca" family="Xanthidae" genus="Monodaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,582,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="44">Monodaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A future revision of these two genera should clarify the characters that are more reliable. While morphological characters are needed for the identification of the species, molecular characters may be more helpful in finding natural generic groups among these xanthids.
</paragraph>
